</a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>When you run a docker container, you may want to keep it running even if the main process is finished. For example, you may want to keep the container running to check the logs or to debug the container. In this case, you can use the <code class=\"language-text\">tail -f /dev/null</code> command to keep the container running.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\"><span class=\"token function\">docker</span> run <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-d</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span>image-name<span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span> <span class=\"token function\">tail</span> <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-f</span> /dev/null</code></pre></div>\n<p>Then we could use the <code class=\"language-text\">docker exec</code> command to enter the container when you need it.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\"><span class=\"token function\">docker</span> <span class=\"token builtin class-name\">exec</span> <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-it</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span>container-id<span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span> /bin/bash</code></pre></div>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/2025-02-12-How-to-Keep-a-Docker-Container-Running//posts/how-to-keep-a-docker-container-running","tagSlugs":["/tag/virtualization/","/tag/docker/"]},"frontmatter":{"date":"2025-02-12T17:00:00.000Z","description":"a useful tip to keep a docker container running.","tags":["Virtualization","Docker"],"title":"How to Keep a Docker Container Running","socialImage":{"publicURL":"/static/6423d7a45e08781936705ee4c2bb8160/docker-daemon.jpg"}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/2025-02-12-How-to-Keep-a-Docker-Container-Running//posts/how-to-keep-a-docker-container-running"}},"staticQueryHashes":["251939775","288581551","401334301"],"slicesMap":{}}